# Cursor Rules for Go DDD Architecture (Updated)

# Overview
This repository follows DDD + Hexagonal Architecture.
- For new code, follow these rules strictly.
- For existing code, preserve behavior and move incrementally.

# Architecture Layers
Layers:
- domain: pure business logic
- application: use cases, orchestration
- adapters: HTTP, DB, Redis, Kafka
- platform: logger, config, clock
- cmd: server entry point

Dependency direction:
HTTP -> Application -> Domain
DB/Redis/Kafka -> Domain interfaces
Domain must never depend on any external layer.

# Folder Structure (Flattened, Feature-Based)
Use a vertical slice per feature:

<feature>/
  store/
    write/           # Optional: commands (POST/PUT/DELETE)
      dto.go         # Write request/response structs
      postgres.go    # Write repository
    read/            # Optional: queries (GET)
      dto.go         # Read request/response structs
      postgres.go    # Read repository (optimized queries)
  const.go           # Feature-level constants
  http.go            # HTTP routes / handlers
  model.go           # Domain entities & value objects
  service.go         # Application use cases

Notes:
- store/ contains DB and DTOs only.
- Optional read/write separation allows CQRS-style organization.
- HTTP DTOs live in store/dto.go (or store/read/dto.go & store/write/dto.go)
- Domain logic stays in model.go
- Application logic stays in service.go
- Handlers in http.go are thin: parse -> call service -> respond

# Domain Layer Rules
Contains:
- Entities
- Value objects
- Domain services
- Repository interfaces

Must NOT import:
net/http, database/sql, pgx, redis, gin, echo, grpc, or any framework

Example:
type CartRepository interface {
  Save(ctx context.Context, cart *Cart) error
  GetByID(ctx context.Context, id string) (*Cart, error)
}

# Application Layer Rules
- Implements use cases.
- Each use case is a struct with dependencies.

Example:
type CreateCart struct {
  repo domain.CartRepository
}

func (uc *CreateCart) Execute(ctx context.Context, merchantID string) (*domain.Cart, error)

Imports allowed: domain, context
Must NOT import: http, postgres, redis, frameworks

# HTTP Adapter Rules
- Handlers live in the feature package (http.go)
- Handlers must only:
  - Parse request
  - Call application use case
  - Return response
- Must not contain business logic

Optional read/write separation:
store/
  read/dto.go         # GET requests/responses
  read/postgres.go    # Query repository
  write/dto.go        # POST/PUT requests/responses
  write/postgres.go   # Command repository

Example:
func LoginHandler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
  var req store.WriteLoginRequest
  json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&req)
  user, _ := service.LoginUser(req.Email, req.Password)
  json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(store.WriteLoginResponse{UserID: user.ID})
}

# Database Adapter Rules
- Implements domain repository interfaces
- Can import: domain, pgx, sqlc
- Must never contain business logic

# Platform Layer Rules
- Cross-cutting: logger, config, clock, tracing
- Must not contain business logic

# Testing Rules
- Unit Tests:
  - Domain: test business rules
  - Application: mock repositories
  - HTTP: test parsing, validation, response
- Integration Tests:
  - Live in adapters
  - Use testcontainers if database required
  - Flow tests (e.g., payload_flow_test.go) exercise read/write interactions
- E2E / Smoke Tests:
  - Critical paths: login -> cart -> order -> report
  - Use http_e2e_flow_test.go and read_smoke_test.go

# Naming Rules
- Use clear names: create_cart.go, get_cart.go, cart_handler.go, cart_repository.go
- Avoid generic names: service.go, manager.go, utils.go

# Vertical Slice Rule
- All code for a feature lives together

Example cart feature:
cart/
  store/           # DB + DTOs
  const.go
  http.go
  model.go
  service.go

# Documentation Rules
- Keep docs in sync with api/openapi.yaml and code
- Only document implemented or planned endpoints; mark drafts clearly
